<?php
$designOptions = array("a" => "Completely randomized design", "b" => "Randomized block design", "c" => "Matched pairs design", "d" => "Factorial design");

return array(
    "overview" => "A strong experiment creates a fair comparison. This lesson develops the language and logic needed to choose treatments, assign experimental units, control outside conditions, replicate, block important differences, and justify a causal conclusion.",
    "objectives" => array(
        "Identify experimental units, subjects, factors, levels, treatments, and response variables.",
        "Explain the roles of comparison, control, random assignment, and replication.",
        "Choose among completely randomized, randomized block, matched pairs, and factorial designs.",
        "Count treatments when an experiment includes multiple factors.",
        "Draw and evaluate an experimental design and state an appropriate conclusion."
    ),
    "prerequisites" => array("Distinguish experiments from observational studies.", "Identify explanatory and response variables.", "Understand why confounding weakens causal claims."),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Experimental unit", "The smallest unit to which a treatment is applied; a human unit is often called a subject or participant."),
        array("Factor", "An explanatory variable deliberately manipulated by researchers."),
        array("Level", "One specific value or category of a factor."),
        array("Treatment", "One complete experimental condition; with several factors, one combination of levels."),
        array("Response variable", "The measured outcome used to compare treatments."),
        array("Control group", "A baseline group receiving no treatment, standard treatment, placebo, or ordinary conditions."),
        array("Random assignment", "Using chance to place experimental units into treatment groups."),
        array("Replication", "Applying each treatment to enough independent experimental units to distinguish effects from natural variation."),
        array("Block", "A group of similar experimental units formed before random assignment."),
        array("Interaction", "A pattern in which the effect of one factor changes across levels of another factor.")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "Translate the Research Question Into a Design", "content" => array(
            "<p>The <strong>experimental unit</strong> is the smallest unit that independently receives a treatment. It may be a student, plant, website visitor, manufactured product, classroom, or school. If an entire classroom receives one teaching method, the classroom is the experimental unit even though scores are collected from individual students. Treating every student as independently assigned would overstate the amount of replication.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>factor</strong> is a variable researchers manipulate, and its <strong>levels</strong> are the chosen settings. If a study changes music condition among silence, instrumental music, and music with lyrics, there is one factor with three levels. A <strong>treatment</strong> is the complete condition received. With one factor, each level is a treatment. With several factors, a treatment is a combination of levels.</p>",
            "<p>The <strong>response variable</strong> must be operationally clear. \"Learning\" is vague; \"score out of 20 on the same delayed quiz given 48 hours later\" can be measured consistently. Researchers should decide the response before examining results to avoid choosing whichever outcome makes a treatment appear successful.</p>",
            array("type" => "formula", "label" => "Counting factorial treatments", "html" => "<p>If factor A has \\(a\\) levels and factor B has \\(b\\) levels, a full factorial design has \\(a\\times b\\) treatments.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "The Four Principles of a Fair Comparison", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Comparison</strong> means observing at least two conditions. Without a baseline, a change could reflect time, expectations, practice, outside events, or ordinary variation. A control group may receive no treatment, a placebo, normal conditions, or the current standard treatment. Ethical experiments do not automatically withhold effective standard care.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Random assignment</strong> uses chance to create treatment groups. Its purpose is to distribute both known and unknown background characteristics without researcher choice. Randomization does not guarantee identical groups in one experiment; it makes systematic imbalance less likely and allows probability to describe remaining differences.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Control</strong> keeps other conditions as similar as practical: same instructions, time, room, equipment, follow-up, and scoring. Control does not mean controlling participants. It means preventing treatment groups from differing in ways that provide rival explanations.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Replication</strong> applies each treatment to enough independent units. Measuring one plant 100 times gives information about measurement consistency, not 100 independent plants. Replication estimates natural variation and makes an accidental result less likely to dominate.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "A useful memory aid", "html" => "<p>Strong experiments <strong>compare</strong> conditions, <strong>randomize</strong> assignment, <strong>control</strong> other influences, and <strong>replicate</strong> across independent units.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Completely Randomized and Block Designs", "content" => array(
            "<p>In a <strong>completely randomized design</strong>, all experimental units enter one assignment pool and are randomly allocated directly to treatments. One hundred students could be randomly assigned, 50 to App A and 50 to App B, and later complete the same assessment. This design is efficient when units are reasonably similar or no major background variable needs special protection.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>randomized block design</strong> first groups units that are similar on an important characteristic, then randomizes treatments separately within every block. Students might be blocked by prior achievement as beginning, intermediate, and advanced. Within each level, students are randomly assigned to two teaching methods. Blocking ensures both methods are compared among similar students and removes predictable block-to-block variation from the treatment comparison.</p>",
            "<p>Blocking is not the same as stratified sampling. Both form groups, but stratification selects a sample from every population subgroup. Blocking occurs after experimental units are available and assigns treatments within groups. The first supports representation; the second improves an experimental comparison.</p>",
            array("type" => "example", "label" => "When to block", "html" => "<p>Block on a variable strongly related to the response and known before treatment, such as baseline score, location, or device type. Too many tiny blocks complicate the design and may make treatment assignment impossible.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Matched Pairs", "content" => array(
            "<p>A <strong>matched pairs design</strong> is a special block design in which each block contains two comparable observations. Researchers can pair similar individuals and randomly assign one treatment to each person, or let the same individual receive both treatments in a random order. Each pair provides a direct local comparison.</p>",
            "<p>For a website interface study, every user might complete one task with Design A and another comparable task with Design B. Randomly assigning half to A-then-B and half to B-then-A protects against order effects. Because each person acts as their own comparison, stable individual differences such as typing speed are reduced.</p>",
            "<p>Matched pairs does not require twins or visually similar people. Matching should use variables relevant to the response. Repeated-treatment designs must consider practice, fatigue, and carryover. If the first condition changes performance in the second, a long enough break, fresh task, counterbalanced order, or separate-person pairing may be needed.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Factorial Designs and Interactions", "content" => array(
            "<p>A <strong>factorial design</strong> studies every combination of two or more factors. Suppose notifications have two levels (reminder or none) and rewards have two levels (badge or points). The four treatments are reminder-badge, reminder-points, no-reminder-badge, and no-reminder-points. Randomly assigning units among all combinations allows researchers to study two questions in one coherent experiment.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>main effect</strong> is the average effect of one factor across levels of the other. An <strong>interaction</strong> occurs when the effect of one factor depends on the other. Perhaps reminders improve completion when paired with points but make no difference with badges. Reporting only the average reminder effect would hide that conditional pattern.</p>",
            "<p>Factorial designs can be efficient but require enough replication in every treatment combination. The design diagram should show the full path: experimental units, random assignment, treatment groups, common measurement, and comparison. A conclusion should identify the response, direction of the effect, represented units, and uncertainty rather than simply declaring a treatment \"works.\"</p>",
            array("type" => "note", "label" => "Design diagram", "html" => "<p>Units \\(\\rightarrow\\) random assignment \\(\\rightarrow\\) treatment groups \\(\\rightarrow\\) same response measurement \\(\\rightarrow\\) compare results.</p>")
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Two-factor study plan", "scenario" => "Researchers vary music condition (silence, instrumental, lyrics) and study duration (20 or 40 minutes).", "steps" => array("Music and study duration are two factors.", "Music has 3 levels; duration has 2 levels.", "A full factorial design contains \\(3\\times2=6\\) treatments.", "Students should be randomly assigned among the six combinations, with enough students in each, and complete the same assessment."), "conclusion" => "The design can estimate main effects and whether the effect of duration changes by music condition."),
        array("title" => "Choosing a block", "scenario" => "A school compares two math programs, and prior math score strongly predicts the final test.", "steps" => array("Prior score is known before treatment and strongly related to the response.", "Create score blocks such as beginning, intermediate, and advanced.", "Within every block, randomly assign students to Program A or B.", "Use the same time, curriculum goals, and final assessment across groups."), "conclusion" => "Randomized blocking compares programs among students with similar starting achievement."),
        array("title" => "Repeated interface comparison", "scenario" => "Each user tests Interfaces A and B while researchers measure task time.", "steps" => array("Each user can act as a matched pair because both times come from the same person.", "Randomly assign half to A first and half to B first to counterbalance practice and fatigue.", "Use comparable tasks and the same device conditions.", "For each person, calculate the difference between A and B time, then compare the differences."), "conclusion" => "The matched design reduces user-to-user speed variation while protecting against order effects."),
        array("title" => "Diagnosing a confounded experiment", "scenario" => "App A is taught by Teacher A in the morning; App B is taught by Teacher B in the afternoon.", "steps" => array("App, teacher, and time of day all change together.", "Any score difference could be caused by one or a combination of those factors.", "Randomly assign students to app within each teacher or have teachers deliver both apps under matched schedules.", "Keep instructions, time, and scoring common."), "conclusion" => "The original design cannot isolate the app effect; randomization and control must separate it from teacher and time."),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("Random assignment means randomly selecting participants.", "Assignment places existing units into treatments; selection chooses units from a population."),
        array("A control group receives nothing.", "It may receive a placebo, ordinary conditions, or the current standard treatment."),
        array("Replication means repeated measurements on one unit.", "True treatment replication requires multiple independent experimental units."),
        array("Blocking and stratified sampling are the same.", "Blocking organizes treatment assignment; stratification organizes sample selection."),
        array("Matched pairs requires twins.", "Pairs may be the same person under both treatments or people matched on response-relevant features."),
        array("Every experiment needs a placebo.", "Placebos are useful when expectations matter and a credible inactive comparison is ethical, but many experiments compare active conditions without one.")
    ),
    "why" => array(
        "A causal answer depends more on the comparison than on complicated mathematics. Randomization, control, and replication turn a difference in outcomes into evidence about a treatment rather than a difference that was built into the groups.",
        "These principles apply to classroom programs, product A/B tests, sports training, manufacturing, and medical trials. They also help students notice when a report calls something an experiment even though no treatment was fairly assigned."
    ),
    "knowledge_check" => array(
        stats_numeric("kc1", "A study has 3 levels of notification and 2 levels of reward. How many factorial treatments are there?", 6, "<p>Every notification level pairs with every reward level: \\(3\\times2=6\\).</p>", "Multiply the level counts.", "foundational", array("treatments")),
        stats_classify("kc2", "All units are randomly assigned directly to one of three treatments.", $designOptions, "a", "<p>There is one assignment pool with direct randomization, so the design is completely randomized.</p>", "No blocks or pairs appear.", "foundational", array("design")),
        stats_classify("kc3", "Units are grouped by baseline score, then treatments are randomized within each group.", $designOptions, "b", "<p>Baseline-score groups are blocks and randomization occurs inside them.</p>", "Similar groups first, assignment second.", "foundational", array("design"))
    ),
    "guided_practice" => array(
        stats_written("g1", "short-response", "A classroom receives one teaching method. Is the experimental unit the student or classroom? Explain.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The classroom is the experimental unit because treatment is applied to the class as a whole. Student scores are observations within that unit.</p>", "Find the smallest unit independently assigned.", "proficient", array("experimental unit")),
        stats_numeric("g2", "A design has factor levels 2, 4, and 3. How many treatment combinations?", 24, "<p>A full factorial combines every level: \\(2\\times4\\times3=24\\).</p>", "Multiply across factors.", "foundational", array("treatments")),
        stats_classify("g3", "Similar athletes are paired; a coin decides which athlete in each pair receives a new routine.", $designOptions, "c", "<p>Each pair is a two-unit block, making this matched pairs.</p>", "Pairs are the smallest blocks.", "proficient", array("matched pairs")),
        stats_classify("g4", "Every combination of two screen colours and three button sizes is tested.", $designOptions, "d", "<p>All combinations of multiple factors define a factorial design.</p>", "Look for every combination.", "foundational", array("factorial")),
        stats_written("g5", "short-response", "Explain why random assignment supports causation.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Chance tends to balance known and unknown background variables across treatments, so a later systematic response difference has fewer competing explanations and can be attributed to treatment more credibly.</p>", "Randomization addresses starting differences.", "proficient", array("random assignment")),
        stats_written("g6", "error-analysis", "A researcher calls 100 repeated measurements on one battery '100 replications.' Correct the claim.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> These are repeated measurements of one experimental unit. Independent replication would apply the treatment to many separate batteries.</p>", "Measurement count is not unit count.", "proficient", array("replication")),
        stats_written("g7", "short-response", "Draw a text design for comparing two study apps with 80 students.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> 80 students \\(\\rightarrow\\) random assignment \\(\\rightarrow\\) 40 use App A and 40 use App B \\(\\rightarrow\\) same four-week period and assessment \\(\\rightarrow\\) compare mean scores.</p>", "Include units, assignment, treatments, response, comparison.", "proficient", array("diagram")),
        stats_written("g8", "short-response", "Choose a design for two interfaces when every participant can test both, and address order.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Use matched pairs with each person testing both interfaces. Randomly assign half to A-then-B and half to B-then-A, use comparable tasks, and compare within-person times.</p>", "Each person can be their own control.", "advanced", array("design selection"))
    ),
    "independent_practice" => array(
        stats_numeric("i1", "Four music levels and three lighting levels produce how many treatments?", 12, "<p>\\(4\\times3=12\\) treatment combinations.</p>", "Multiply levels.", "foundational", array("treatments")),
        stats_numeric("i2", "Two reward levels, two reminder levels, and three frequency levels produce how many treatments?", 12, "<p>\\(2\\times2\\times3=12\\).</p>", "Every combination is included.", "foundational", array("treatments")),
        stats_classify("i3", "Students are blocked by school, then randomly assigned methods within each school.", $designOptions, "b", "<p>School forms the blocks and assignment occurs within each.</p>", "The grouping happens before randomization.", "proficient", array("block")),
        stats_classify("i4", "A coin assigns each of 120 products directly to one of two packaging tests.", $designOptions, "a", "<p>All units enter direct random assignment, so the design is completely randomized.</p>", "One assignment pool.", "foundational", array("design")),
        stats_written("i5", "short-response", "Identify factors, levels, treatments, and response when reminder type has 3 levels, points have 2 levels, and completion is measured.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Factors are reminder type and points condition. Their levels are the three reminder types and two points settings. There are six treatments. The response is the defined completion measure.</p>", "Separate factors from their settings.", "proficient", array("vocabulary")),
        stats_written("i6", "short-response", "Why might standard treatment be a better control than no treatment?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Withholding an effective standard may be unethical and would answer a less useful question. Comparing a new method with current practice tests whether it improves on what people already receive.</p>", "Control means baseline, not necessarily nothing.", "proficient", array("control")),
        stats_written("i7", "short-response", "Explain the difference between control and a control group.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Control is the broad principle of holding outside conditions similar. A control group is one baseline treatment group used for comparison.</p>", "One is a principle; one is a group.", "proficient", array("control")),
        stats_written("i8", "error-analysis", "A study assigns App A to volunteers and compares them with nonvolunteers using App B. What is wrong?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Treatment is confounded with willingness to volunteer. Randomly assign eligible participants to A or B so motivation and other characteristics are not systematically tied to one app.</p>", "Groups differ before treatment.", "advanced", array("confounding")),
        stats_written("i9", "short-response", "Explain an interaction between notification and reward type.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> An interaction would occur if reminders increase completion with points but have little effect or decrease completion with badges. The reminder effect changes depending on reward type.</p>", "The effect of one factor must depend on the other.", "advanced", array("interaction")),
        stats_written("i10", "short-response", "Design a complete experiment testing whether a study timer improves quiz scores.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Recruit eligible students with consent; students are experimental units. Randomly assign enough students to a timer app or standard study procedure, keep study material, time, instructions, and quiz common, and compare quiz scores. Record prior score for possible blocking, protect privacy, report attrition, and conclude causation only for participants similar to those studied.</p>", "Cover units, treatment, comparison, assignment, control, replication, response, ethics, and conclusion.", "advanced", array("full design"))
    ),
